Load SQLite Data

  • Had to manipulate and rename location data to create structures for OD (Origin-Destination)
  • library Connected to SQLite database on rail locations
con <- dbConnect(RSQLite::SQLite(), "rail.db")
# Show List of Tables
# as.data.frame(dbListTables(con))

Select relevant data from database

  • Data thinned out to only represent STRACNET and Connecting Lines.
  • Loading railheads are NOT represented.
  • Had to select nodal and line data to create Linestrings for Leaflet.
  • Had to make sure the latitude/Longitude data was in correct format (numeric types with - for longitude data).
# Get table
Q_Node_FromXY <- dbReadTable(con, 'Q_Node_FromXY') %>%
  dplyr::select(-OBJECTID) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(From_X = (-1 * as.numeric(From_X)), From_Y = (1 * as.numeric(From_Y)))

Q_Node <- dbReadTable(con,"Q_Node") %>%
  dplyr::select(FRANODEID, X,Y) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(X = (-1 * as.numeric(X)), Y = (1 * as.numeric(Y))) %>%
  dplyr::rename(geo_code = FRANODEID)

Q_Node_ToXY <- dbReadTable(con,"Q_Node_ToXY") %>%
  dplyr::select(-OBJECTID) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(To_X = (-1 * as.numeric(To_X)), To_Y = (1 * as.numeric(To_Y)))

od <- dbReadTable(con,"Q_FROM_TO_Miles") %>%
  dplyr::rename(geo_code1 = FRFRANODE, geo_code2 = TOFRANODE ) %>%
  dplyr::select(-OBJECTID)

Renamed variables to support OD Library

  • Create Geocode named references for From-To data variables
  • From and To structured accordingly.
head(od)

Created a SF spatial object to generate a RAILID geocode reference object

  • Needed to do this in order to ude OD and STPLANR libraries
  • Updated Coordinate Reference System (CRS) to 3857 reference (WS84)
node_data  <- st_as_sf(x = Q_Node, 
                        coords = c("X", "Y"),
                        crs = 3857 )
# str(node_data)

Use OD Library to create a From-To Polyline Object

stracnet_lines = stplanr::od2line(od, node_data)

head(stracnet_lines)

Generate Power Projection Platform and Port Data for Leaflet

power_projection_platform <- read_excel("power_projection_platform.xlsx") %>%
  select(1:8,)

View Power Projection Data

head(power_projection_platform, 10)

Use Leaflet to show STRACNET and Power Projection Platforms

  • Generate Polyline Object for STRACNET and Connecting lines
  • Generate Power Projection Platform markers
leaflet(stracnet_lines) %>%
  setView(-95.7889, 38.735, zoom = 5) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Esri.WorldStreetMap)  %>%  # Add default OpenStreetMap map tiles
  addPolylines(  color = "#027F00", weight = 3, opacity = .5) %>%
  addMarkers(data = power_projection_platform, ~PPP_LONG, ~PPP_Lat, popup = ~PPP_Installation, label = ~PPP_Installation) %>%
  addMarkers(data = power_projection_platform, ~SPOE_lon, ~SPOE_lat, popup = ~Designated_SPOE, label = ~Designated_SPOE)

Try the Plot function to review the line shapes

plot(stracnet_lines)
